	<LINE>ASSOCIATION FOR THE RELIEF OF INCU-</LINE>
	<LINE>RABLES FOR GLASGOW AND THE WEST</LINE>
	<LINE>OF SCOTLAND.</LINE>
	<LINE>Office— 68 Bath Street.</LINE>
	<LINE>This association has for its objects the establishment</LINE>
	<LINE>and main tenance of one or more hospitals for the relief of</LINE>
	<LINE>persons in Glasgow and the West of Scotland labour-</LINE>
	<LINE>ing under chronic and incurable diseases, and the</LINE>
	<LINE>aiding of such persons in their own homes. The</LINE>
	<LINE>association has an institution at Kirkintilloch, Dum-</LINE>
	<LINE>bartonshire, known as Broomhill Home, accommodating</LINE>
	<LINE>62 patients, and spends a large sum monthly in assist-</LINE>
	<LINE>ing about 150 incurables in their own houses. The</LINE>
	<LINE>whole affairs of the association are managed by a board</LINE>
	<LINE>of directors consisting of twenty-one members, in addi-</LINE>
	<LINE>tion to Miss Beatrice Clugston, as promoter, and twenty-</LINE>
	<LINE>eight ex officio members. Chairman of the Association,</LINE>
	<LINE>the Hon. John Ure, Lord Provost ; deputy-chairmen,</LINE>
	<LINE>Sir Peter Coats of Auchendrane ; Peter Denny,</LINE>
	<LINE>Esq., and Dr. A. Buchanan; hon. treasurer, P. B.</LINE>
	<LINE>Junor, Esq., Clydesdale Bank, 14 Miller Street;</LINE>
	<LINE>examining-medical officers, Dr. J. Wallace Anderson,</LINE>
	<LINE>4 Burnbank Terrace, and Dr. A. Wallace, 4 Newton</LINE>
	<LINE>Place ; visiting medical-officers, Drs. D. P. Stewart</LINE>
	<LINE>and W. Whitelaw, Kirkintilloch; matron, Mrs.</LINE>
	<LINE>M'Laugbhn; secretary, Mr. W. T. M'Auslane, 68</LINE>
	<LINE>Bath St.; almoner, Mr. John Grant.</LINE>
	<LINE>LITTLE SISTERS OF THE POOR, AND ST.</LINE>
	<LINE>JOSEPH'S HOME FOR THE AGED.</LINE>
	<LINE>180 Gakngad Hill.</LINE>
	<LINE>This institution was founded at Glasgow in 1862,</LINE>
	<LINE>and contains now 225 aged poor of both sexes.</LINE>
	<LINE>The Sisters have no funds whatever ; they support</LINE>
	<LINE>the aged poor by whatever public charity affords, and</LINE>
	<LINE>therefore most gratefully accept cast-off clothes, furni-</LINE>
	<LINE>ture, donations in money, or anything that may be</LINE>
	<LINE>offered. Although the building is completed, dona-</LINE>
	<LINE>tions for defraying the expenses are humbly solicited.</LINE>
	<LINE>For admission apply at the institution.</LINE>
	<LINE>The Home is open to visitors daily from 11 o'clock</LINE>
	<LINE>a.m. till 4 o'clock p.m.</LINE>
